<Base title="5 Best English Courses for Travel: Your Ticket to the World" description="Master the essential phrases and confidence you need to navigate any destination with ease.">
<article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
  <div class="mb-8">
    <span class="text-sm text-gray-400">Guide · Updated April 2026</span>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mt-1 mb-4">5 Best English Courses for Travel: Your Ticket to the World</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-500">Master the essential phrases and confidence you need to navigate any destination with ease.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
    <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-lg">Top Choice</p>
        <p class="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-700">italki (Travel Specialists)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="text-right">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Best for</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-blue-700">Real-world Practice</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Why General English Isn't Enough for Travel</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4 leading-relaxed">When you are standing at a train station in London or checking into a hotel in New York, you do not need to know complex grammar rules. You need functional language. Travel English focuses on survival skills: ordering food, asking for directions, handling transport delays, and making small talk with locals.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">1. italki (Customized Travel Lessons)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The fastest way to prepare for a trip is to role-play with a native speaker. On italki, you can find tutors who specialize in travel English. They can simulate scenarios like clearing customs or reporting a lost passport. This builds the muscle memory you need when you are actually on the road.</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-600 mb-6">
    <li>Personalized role-play for your specific destination</li>
    <li>Flexible scheduling to fit your pre-trip planning</li>
    <li>Focus on listening to different accents</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">2. Duolingo (Vocabulary Foundations)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4 leading-relaxed">For absolute beginners, Duolingo is a great starting point to build a core vocabulary of travel nouns and verbs. It is free and easy to use during your commute. However, it should be used as a supplement to speaking practice, not a replacement.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">3. Babbel (Dialogue-Based Learning)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Babbel offers specific "Travel" modules that focus on realistic dialogues. The speech recognition tool helps you polish your pronunciation so you are understood by locals the first time you speak.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Verdict</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Start with Duolingo three months before your trip to build your vocabulary. One month before you leave, book five sessions on italki to practice your speaking. This approach ensures you have both the words and the confidence to use them.</p>

  <div class="bg-blue-600 rounded-xl p-8 text-white mt-12">
    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Ready to explore the world?</h3>
    <p class="mb-6">Find a travel English tutor on italki and start practicing for your next adventure.</p>
    <a href="/reviews/italki/" class="bg-white text-blue-600 px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-bold hover:bg-gray-100 transition-colors">Find a Travel Tutor</a>
  </div>
</article>
</Base>
